name: This Place is Eeek!
description: How to Live in a Dying City, A Guide.

name: Issue Four [stories my parents used to tell]
description: Issue Four of Things We're Not Going to Talk About. First published November 2012. Six more anonymous interviews on the stories we were told, the people our parents were, and how they made us who we are now. Because the story becomes something in your own mind, and there may be details you want, but you ponder on these ambiguities for long enough and you come to your own conclusions, you use your own imagination, and eventually your version of the story becomes real enough for you to be satisfied with. 28 pages, B & W.

name: Issue Three [things i used to believe]
description: Issue Three of Things We're Not Going to Talk About, title inspired by episode #378 of This American Life. First published July 2012, reprinted November 2012. Six more anonymous interviews on God, death, sex and womanhood. "My notions of what grief should be are based on fictional representations of it. I have this idea that true grieving is supposed to be a short, ephemeral burst of wailing and tearing of hair and uncontainable agony and it’s all very cathartic for a while and it’s followed by a numbness, which in turn, eventually fades away." 28 pages, B & W.

name: Issue Two [arguments i meant to finish but didn't]
description: Issue two of Things We're Not Going to Talk About. First published May 2012, reprinted November 2012. This issue features six more anonymous interviews on conversations left unfinished, staircase wit, L'esprit de l'escalier. We're talking about marriage, we're talking about breaking up, we're talking about drugs and we're talking about John Malkovich. "But if I had been given the chance to say what I really wanted to say. Suppose she couldn’t talk back. Suppose she was paralysed or catatonic and she couldn’t move her body and therefore couldn’t hit me. I’d probably tell her that it’s unlikely that I’ll be getting married." 24 pages, B & W

name: Issue One [hearts i tried not to break but did]
description: The first issue of Things We're Not Going to Talk About. First published February 2012, reprinted November 2012. This issue features six anonymous interviews on love, loss, regret and whiskey. "I can still remember a lot of things about that last day really clearly. I can remember vividly the scent of the perfume you were wearing. Your leather jacket. I remember hugging you and feeling how thin you were." 24 pages, B & W
